1
00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:02,480
Six Minute English.

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:05,699
From bbclearningenglish.com.

3
00:00:07,739 --> 00:00:08,320
Hello.

4
00:00:08,320 --> 00:00:11,519
This is Six Minute English from BBC Learning English.

5
00:00:11,519 --> 00:00:12,240
I'm Neil.

6
00:00:12,240 --> 00:00:13,299
And I'm Beth.

7
00:00:13,515 --> 00:00:19,615
It smells delicious sizzling in oil and it's great for keeping vampires away.

8
00:00:19,615 --> 00:00:22,035
But don't eat it on a first date.

9
00:00:22,155 --> 00:00:25,155
I'm talking, of course, about garlic.

10
00:00:25,195 --> 00:00:26,594
Neil, do you like garlic?

11
00:00:26,619 --> 00:00:27,680
Oh, yes.

12
00:00:27,680 --> 00:00:28,720
I love garlic.

13
00:00:28,720 --> 00:00:31,439
I had a very garlicky meal last night.

14
00:00:31,439 --> 00:00:33,860
I know I can smell it from here.

15
00:00:35,019 --> 00:00:38,320
Here is Jason Chan, an Australian chef

16
00:00:38,320 --> 00:00:43,295
who specialises in Asian cuisine and Paul Erik Jensen,

17
00:00:43,255 --> 00:00:45,595
a Danish chef living in France,

18
00:00:45,595 --> 00:00:50,395
talking about their love of garlic to BBC World Service Programme, The Food Chain.

19
00:00:50,395 --> 00:00:53,835
I love garlic because it's a versatile ingredient

20
00:00:53,835 --> 00:00:57,809
that can be used for cooking and offers various health benefits.

21
00:00:57,809 --> 00:00:59,010
We use it a lot.

22
00:00:59,010 --> 00:01:02,930
And so from stocks to soups and in vegetable dishes,

23
00:01:02,930 --> 00:01:06,869
meat dishes, there's very certain a clove of garlic in somewhere.

24
00:01:07,070 --> 00:01:07,490
Yeah.

25
00:01:07,490 --> 00:01:09,750
It's unimaginable not using garlic.

26
00:01:09,725 --> 00:01:15,684
Jason loves garlic because it's versatile, meaning it can be used in many different ways.

27
00:01:15,725 --> 00:01:22,884
And Paul thinks cooking without garlic is unimaginable, meaning it's difficult to imagine because it would be so bad.

28
00:01:23,160 --> 00:01:25,520
Love garlic or hate it?

29
00:01:25,480 --> 00:01:31,039
In this episode, we'll be finding out more about this versatile, strong smelling food.

30
00:01:31,240 --> 00:01:35,199
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases as well.

31
00:01:35,165 --> 00:01:42,385
And remember, you can find all the vocabulary from this episode on our website bbclearningenglish.com.

32
00:01:42,385 --> 00:01:44,385
Now, Beth, I have a question for you.

33
00:01:44,385 --> 00:01:48,784
It's a little known fact that of the 600 varieties of garlic,

34
00:01:48,784 --> 00:01:51,440
many grew only in the Former Soviet Union

35
00:01:51,440 --> 00:01:53,200
and were unavailable in the West

36
00:01:53,200 --> 00:01:56,580
until the fall of communism in the nineteen nineties.

37
00:01:56,540 --> 00:02:02,080
So which of the following varieties of garlic grew in the Former USSR?

38
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:07,675
Is it a, Rock and Bowl b fire or c re cig?

39
00:02:07,634 --> 00:02:09,495
Oh, I have no idea.

40
00:02:09,495 --> 00:02:11,515
I'm going to guess fire.

41
00:02:11,475 --> 00:02:12,295
Okay.

42
00:02:12,295 --> 00:02:15,515
We'll find out if you're right at the end of the programme.

43
00:02:15,475 --> 00:02:18,315
Garlic is much more than just a cooking ingredient.

44
00:02:18,490 --> 00:02:25,890
For centuries, garlic was an important food throughout ancient Egypt, Greece and Rome as well as India and China.

45
00:02:26,010 --> 00:02:30,369
It was the Roman Empire that brought garlic to European countries like France.

46
00:02:30,745 --> 00:02:35,085
And everywhere garlic grew, it was praised for its health giving powers.

47
00:02:35,085 --> 00:02:47,299
Here, BBC presenter Rumella Das Gupta asks author and garlic expert Robin Cherry about garlic's medicinal uses on BBC World Service's The Food Chain.

48
00:02:47,260 --> 00:02:51,840
And what kind of illnesses or conditions would they have treated, for instance?

49
00:02:51,840 --> 00:02:58,820
Everything from cancer, scurvy, the plague, respiratory ailments it was used as an aphrodisiac.

50
00:02:58,865 --> 00:03:02,265
Garlic was used to treat respiratory ailments.

51
00:03:02,225 --> 00:03:06,245
An ailment is another word for an illness or minor health problem.

52
00:03:06,245 --> 00:03:09,625
So a respiratory ailment is an illness of the lungs.

53
00:03:09,665 --> 00:03:17,910
In ancient Greece, garlic was also used as an aphrodisiac a food or drink believed to increase sexual desire.

54
00:03:18,190 --> 00:03:24,550
But interestingly, this was the same reason why some cultures avoided eating garlic altogether,

55
00:03:24,670 --> 00:03:28,070
including a religious group from India called Jains.

56
00:03:28,475 --> 00:03:29,295
Yes.

57
00:03:29,295 --> 00:03:32,575
Jainism is an ancient Indian religion like Hinduism

58
00:03:32,575 --> 00:03:37,295
and Buddhism based on the idea of uhimsa or non violence.

59
00:03:37,295 --> 00:03:44,354
But unlike many Hindus and Buddhists, Jains' definition of non violence includes plants and vegetables.

60
00:03:44,850 --> 00:03:48,710
Janes don't eat garlic because uprooting the plant kills both it

61
00:03:48,710 --> 00:03:51,190
and the soil ecosystem it grows in.

62
00:03:51,190 --> 00:03:54,710
Here's Sonal Ved, a Mumbai based cooking show host

63
00:03:54,710 --> 00:04:04,365
and author of many books on Indian cuisine explaining another reason why Jains avoid garlic to BBC World Service program, The Food Chain.

64
00:04:04,365 --> 00:04:10,364
According to Hinduism also, garlic is considered a food which is called the tamsik food.

65
00:04:10,364 --> 00:04:12,065
It is believed to stimulate desire,

66
00:04:12,110 --> 00:04:18,610
passion, aggression, and that's why they abstain from eating those kinds of food

67
00:04:18,610 --> 00:04:23,270
because it is believed to impact your spiritual growth and also your mental clarity.

68
00:04:23,469 --> 00:04:25,910
Jains abstain from eating garlic.

69
00:04:26,275 --> 00:04:30,555
If you abstain from doing something, you choose not to do it.

70
00:04:30,594 --> 00:04:36,615
For example, you might abstain from tobacco or alcohol because you know they're bad for your health.

71
00:04:36,615 --> 00:04:41,595
Like the ancient Greeks, Jains believed that garlic stimulates sexual desire.

72
00:04:41,849 --> 00:04:47,150
The verb to stimulate means encourage it or cause it to develop and grow.

73
00:04:47,150 --> 00:04:53,070
Modern medicine has confirmed some of these ancient beliefs about the health benefits of garlic

74
00:04:53,070 --> 00:04:56,210
including reduced blood pressure and better gut health.

75
00:04:56,525 --> 00:04:57,425
Okay, Neil.

76
00:04:57,425 --> 00:05:00,065
Isn't it time you revealed the answer to your question?

77
00:05:00,065 --> 00:05:00,945
Yes, Beth.

78
00:05:00,945 --> 00:05:05,525
I asked you which variety of garlic grew in the Former USSR.

79
00:05:05,485 --> 00:05:07,265
And I said fire.

80
00:05:07,265 --> 00:05:08,225
Was I right?

81
00:05:08,225 --> 00:05:10,610
You were absolutely correct.

82
00:05:10,610 --> 00:05:11,010
Yay.

83
00:05:11,010 --> 00:05:18,070
Fire or Georgian fire is a hot white garlic from the Republic Of Georgia in the Former Soviet Union.

84
00:05:18,190 --> 00:05:18,690
Okay.

85
00:05:18,690 --> 00:05:26,425
Let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with versatile an adjective meaning to have many different purposes or uses.

86
00:05:26,425 --> 00:05:29,384
The phrase it's unimaginable is used to say

87
00:05:29,384 --> 00:05:31,544
that something is difficult to imagine

88
00:05:31,544 --> 00:05:34,185
because it would be so good or so bad.

89
00:05:34,185 --> 00:05:36,764
An ailment is an illness or health problem.

90
00:05:36,879 --> 00:05:41,880
An aphrodisiac is a food or drink believed to increase sexual desire.

91
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:45,139
If you abstain from something, you choose not to do it.

92
00:05:45,139 --> 00:05:50,360
And finally, to stimulate means to encourage something or cause it to grow.

93
00:05:50,560 --> 00:05:52,900
Once again, our six minutes are up.

94
00:05:52,900 --> 00:06:03,375
If you've enjoyed this episode, then head over to our website bbclearningenglish.com where you'll find a quiz and worksheets to practice the vocabulary you've learnt.

95
00:06:03,770 --> 00:06:05,070
See you again soon.

96
00:06:05,070 --> 00:06:06,590
But for now, it's goodbye.

97
00:06:06,590 --> 00:06:07,490
Goodbye.

98
00:06:08,330 --> 00:06:09,949
Six Minute English.

99
00:06:09,949 --> 00:06:12,669
From bbclearningenglish.com.
